<h3 id="the-leetcode-problem-rewarding-the-wrong-skills">The LeetCode Problem: Rewarding the Wrong Skills</h3>

<p>Ask any developer about LeetCode and youâ€™ll likely get a passionate response. Itâ€™s become a rite of passage for many job seekers in tech, especially those applying to big tech companies like Google, Amazon, and Facebook. The site offers a wealth of algorithmic challenges that many tech companies use as part of their hiring process. As a result, itâ€™s common for developers to spend hours perfecting solutions to problems like reversing a linked list or solving intricate dynamic programming puzzles.</p>

<p>But hereâ€™s the thing: the hardest parts of writing software arenâ€™t typically about solving brainteasers or cracking complex algorithms. The real challenges lie in things like system design, effective collaboration, debugging under pressure, and building scalable applications. Yet, many companies place disproportionate value on these kinds of technical challenges during the interview process, which often results in a focus on narrow, isolated skills that donâ€™t necessarily reflect the day-to-day realities of software engineering.</p>

<p>In fact, a 2018 study published in Communications of the ACM found that while coding challenges can help assess technical skills, they are a poor predictor of success in actual software development projects<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote" rel="footnote" role="doc-noteref">1</a></sup>. This is a big problem because it encourages a â€œcode monkeyâ€ mentalityâ€”one that prioritizes technical prowess without considering the broader skill set needed to succeed in a collaborative, dynamic environment.</p>

<h3 id="the-limits-of-the-code-monkey-mindset">The Limits of the â€œCode Monkeyâ€ Mindset</h3>

<p>When you think of a â€œcode monkey,â€ you might imagine someone who is more focused on writing lines of code than on growing as an engineer or as a communicator. Unfortunately, this mindset is not just unproductiveâ€”itâ€™s also a major roadblock to personal and professional growth.</p>

